ene in operon.</p></fn></table-wrap-foot></table-wrap><p>Although 146 genes were classified as class N, that is, their expression was negatively correlated with Pch and Ler activity, only 35% showed Pch and/or Ler binding in or near their DNA sequences (<xref ref-type="fig" rid="DSM033F5">Fig.&#x000a0;5</xref>). These 40 backbone or K-12 common genes and 11 S-loop genes seemed to be directly regulated by Pch and/or Ler (<xref ref-type="table" rid="DSM033TB3">Table&#x000a0;3</xref>). They include genes encoding regulators, <italic>yhiF</italic>, <italic>gadE</italic>, <italic>gadX</italic>, and <italic>gadW</italic>, and their regulating genes, <italic>gadB</italic>, <italic>hdeA, hdeB, and hdeD</italic>. Two genes, <italic>yhiF</italic> and <italic>gadE</italic>, inhibit the expression of LEE genes,<sup><xref ref-type="bibr" rid="DSM033C27">27</xref></sup> suggesting there is a reciprocal negative interaction between the Pch&#x02013;Ler virulence regulatory system and the YhiF&#x02013;GadE regulatory system.</p><table-wrap id="DSM033TB3" position="float"><label>Table&#x000a0;3</label><caption><p>ORFs in cluster N with binding sites for Pch/Ler</p></caption><table frame="hsides" rules="groups"><colgroup span="1"><col align="left" span="1"/><col align="left" span="1"/><col align="left" span="1"/><col align="left" span="1"/><col align="left" span="1"/></colgroup><thead><tr><th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">ECs#</th><th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Gene/ORF</th><th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Product</th><th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Locus</th><th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Binding*</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td rowspan="1" colspan="1">ECs0079</td><td rowspan="1" colspan="1"><italic>leuL</italic></td><td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Leu operon leader peptide</td><td rowspan="1" colspan="1">K12</td><td rowspan="1" colspan="1">P + L</td></tr><tr><td rowspan="1" colspan="1">ECs0324</td><td rowspan="1" colspan="1"><italic>ykgK</ital